properties.Title: Update To Civil Emergency Alert Issued By Government Of Saskatchewan
properties.Summary:
Description: Update for the Civil Emergency Alert issued by the Government of Saskatchewan. The state of emergency in Saskatchewan remains in effect. UPDATE: Phase 4.2 of Re-Open Saskatchewan is effective June 29. Additional allowable re-openings in Phase 4.2 are: libraries, museums, art galleries, movie and live theatres. The Northwest Region remains in Phase 2 of Re-Open Saskatchewan, however there are some activities and services from other Phases being permitted. Go to the Saskatchewan COVID website listed in the instructions for a complete list of allowable services and activities in the Northwest Region. During all Phases of Re-Open Saskatchewan all public health orders, which includes physical distancing by at least two metres from others, is to be followed and applied in all public and private gatherings.
Expires: 2020-07-06T17:00:00-06:00

Area: Province of Saskatchewan

properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long duration heat event is expected. Daytime high temperatures in the low thirties with overnight lows near 18 are expected until the end of this week. Please refer to your public forecast for further details on expected temperatures. Hot and humid air can also bring deteriorating air quality and can result in the Air Quality Health Index to approach the high risk category. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. The risks are greater for young children, pregnant women, older adults, people with chronic illnesses and people working or exercising outdoors. Watch for the effects of heat illness: swelling, rash, cramps, fainting, heat exhaustion, heat stroke and the worsening of some health conditions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions are favourable for the development of severe thunderstorms this evening. Thunderstorms have formed in Saskatchewan, Montana, and North Dakota. Some of these thunderstorms have the potential to become severe with hail to the size of golf balls, wind gusts in excess of 100 km/h, and rainfall in excess of 100 mm. ### Very large hail can damage property, break windows, dent vehicles and cause serious injury. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Remember, severe thunderstorms can produce tornadoes. Heavy downpours are likely to cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Severe thunderstorm watches are issued when atmospheric conditions are favourable for the development of thunderstorms that could produce one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a line of severe thunderstorms capable of producing rainfall in excess of 100 mm and golf ball sized hail. At 9:18 PM CST Doppler RADAR indicated that this line of severe thunderstorms stretched from Regway to Ceylon and was moving toward the north at 20 km/h. At 9:18 PM CST Doppler RADAR estimates that more than 60 mm of rain has fallen south of Gladmar. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Large hail can damage property and cause injury. Severe thunderstorm warnings are issued when imminent or occurring thunderstorms are likely to produce or are producing one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall.

properties.Title: Update: Flood Warning Issued For Southwestern, Western And Central Regions In Manitoba.
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructures Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a Flood Warning for southwestern, western and central regions of Manitoba. A weather system may release 80 to 150 millimetres of rain in these areas in between June 29 to July 1. Areas in southwest Manitoba, including Virden and Brandon could see up to 175 millimetres of rain during this time. If you are in the affected area, be watchful as local waterways are expected to rise quickly and may cause flooding. There is a potential for overland flooding in low lying areas. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Use caution when driving on all roads as road conditions may have changed. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by local authorities, listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Stay tuned to local media for updates.
Expires: 2020-07-02T16:00:00-05:00

Please refer to your public forecast for further details on expected temperatures. Hot and humid air can also bring deteriorating air quality and can result in the Air Quality Health Index to approach the high risk category. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. The risks are greater for young children, pregnant women, older adults, people with chronic illnesses and people working or exercising outdoors. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
